# Connecting your app to Nocturne

This guide walks you through connecting your app to a Nocturne instance using OAuth 2.0.
By the end, you'll have a working integration that can read glucose entries on behalf of a user.

Nocturne uses **OAuth 2.0 Authorization Code with PKCE** (Proof Key for Code Exchange).
Every client is a public client — there are no client secrets. PKCE replaces the secret,
which makes this flow safe for desktop apps and SPAs. For mobile apps or devices
with limited input, see the [Device Authorization flow guide](/docs/connecting-apps/device-flow).

<Callout type="tip" title="Prefer an SDK for API calls?">
  The code below uses raw HTTP requests to show the OAuth flow end to end. Once you
  have an access token, you don't have to hand-write API calls — official SDKs for
  the V4 API are available in several languages. See <a href="/docs/sdks">SDKs</a>.
</Callout>

## 1. Register your app

Before your app can authenticate users, it needs a `client_id`. Nocturne supports
[Dynamic Client Registration (RFC 7591)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7591) —
your app registers itself by calling a single endpoint.

```typescript
const response = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/register",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      client_name: "GlucoTracker",
      software_id: "com.example.glucotracker",
      redirect_uris: ["glucotracker://oauth/callback"],
      scope: "glucose.read treatments.read",
    }),
  }
);

const registration = await response.json();
// {
//   "client_id": "a1b2c3d4-...",
//   "client_name": "GlucoTracker",
//   "redirect_uris": ["glucotracker://oauth/callback"],
//   "grant_types": ["authorization_code", "refresh_token"],
//   "token_endpoint_auth_method": "none",
//   "software_id": "com.example.glucotracker"
// }
```

Registration is **idempotent per tenant** — if your `software_id` is already registered
on that Nocturne instance, you'll get the existing `client_id` back. Store the `client_id`;
you'll need it for every authorization request.

<Callout type="tip" title="Well-known apps">
  Popular diabetes apps (Trio, Loop, AAPS, xDrip+) are pre-registered in Nocturne
  and get branded consent screens with logos. If you'd like your app added to
  this list, open an issue on the Nocturne GitHub repository.
</Callout>

## 2. Authorize the user

OAuth PKCE works by generating a random secret (`code_verifier`), hashing it
(`code_challenge`), and sending only the hash to the authorization server.
When you exchange the code for tokens later, you prove you started the flow
by sending the original secret.

### Generate the PKCE challenge

```typescript
function generateCodeVerifier(): string {
  const array = new Uint8Array(32);
  crypto.getRandomValues(array);
  return base64UrlEncode(array);
}

async function generateCodeChallenge(verifier: string): Promise<string> {
  const encoder = new TextEncoder();
  const data = encoder.encode(verifier);
  const digest = await crypto.subtle.digest("SHA-256", data);
  return base64UrlEncode(new Uint8Array(digest));
}

function base64UrlEncode(bytes: Uint8Array): string {
  const binary = String.fromCharCode(...bytes);
  return btoa(binary)
    .replace(/\+/g, "-")
    .replace(/\//g, "_")
    .replace(/=+$/, "");
}
```

### Redirect to the authorization endpoint

Build the authorization URL and redirect the user's browser to it:

```typescript
const codeVerifier = generateCodeVerifier();
const codeChallenge = await generateCodeChallenge(codeVerifier);

// Store codeVerifier — you'll need it in step 3
sessionStorage.setItem("pkce_code_verifier", codeVerifier);

const params = new URLSearchParams({
  client_id: registration.client_id,
  redirect_uri: "glucotracker://oauth/callback",
  response_type: "code",
  scope: "glucose.read treatments.read",
  code_challenge: codeChallenge,
  code_challenge_method: "S256",
  state: crypto.randomUUID(), // CSRF protection
});

window.location.href =
  `https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/authorize?${params}`;
```

The user will see a consent screen showing your app name and the requested scopes.
If they approve, Nocturne redirects back to your `redirect_uri` with an authorization code:

```
glucotracker://oauth/callback?code=abc123&state=...
```

If they deny, you'll receive an error instead:

```
glucotracker://oauth/callback?error=access_denied&state=...
```

## 3. Exchange the code for tokens

Once you have the authorization code from the callback, exchange it for an access token
and refresh token:

```typescript
const code = new URL(callbackUrl).searchParams.get("code");
const codeVerifier = sessionStorage.getItem("pkce_code_verifier");

const tokenResponse = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/token",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" },
    body: new URLSearchParams({
      grant_type: "authorization_code",
      code,
      redirect_uri: "glucotracker://oauth/callback",
      client_id: registration.client_id,
      code_verifier: codeVerifier,
    }),
  }
);

const tokens = await tokenResponse.json();
// {
//   "access_token": "eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIs...",
//   "token_type": "Bearer",
//   "expires_in": 3600,
//   "refresh_token": "dGhpcyBpcyBhIHJlZnJl...",
//   "scope": "glucose.read treatments.read"
// }
```

<Callout type="warning" title="Store tokens securely">
  The refresh token is long-lived and grants ongoing access. Store it in your
  platform's secure storage (Keychain on iOS, EncryptedSharedPreferences on Android,
  or an encrypted store on desktop). Never store tokens in plain text or localStorage
  in production.
</Callout>

The authorization code is single-use — if the exchange fails, you'll get an
`invalid_grant` error and the user will need to re-authorize.

## 4. Make API calls

Use the access token as a Bearer token in the `Authorization` header:

```typescript
const response = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/v4/glucose/sensor?limit=10",
  {
    headers: {
      Authorization: `Bearer ${tokens.access_token}`,
    },
  }
);

const { data, pagination } = await response.json();
// {
//   "data": [
//     {
//       "id": "01966c3a-...",
//       "timestamp": "2026-06-25T12:30:00Z",
//       "mills": 1713100800000,
//       "mgdl": 142,
//       "mmol": 7.88,
//       "direction": "Flat",
//       "trend": 4,
//       ...
//     }
//   ],
//   "pagination": { "limit": 10, "offset": 0, "total": 1234 }
// }
```

Results come back as a paginated envelope: the readings are under `data`,
and `pagination` carries `limit`, `offset`, and `total` for paging with
`?limit=&offset=`.

If the token has expired, the API returns `401 Unauthorized`. If the token lacks the
required scope for an endpoint, you'll get `403 Forbidden`.

## 5. Refresh tokens

Access tokens expire (check the `expires_in` value from the token response). When one
expires, use the refresh token to get a new pair:

```typescript
const refreshResponse = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/token",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" },
    body: new URLSearchParams({
      grant_type: "refresh_token",
      refresh_token: tokens.refresh_token,
      client_id: registration.client_id,
    }),
  }
);

const newTokens = await refreshResponse.json();
// Same shape as the original token response —
// new access_token AND new refresh_token
```

<Callout type="danger" title="Refresh tokens rotate">
  Each refresh returns a <strong>new</strong> refresh token and invalidates the old one.
  Always store the latest refresh token. If you replay an old refresh token,
  the entire grant is revoked for security and the user will need to re-authorize.
</Callout>

## 6. Revoking access

When the user signs out or disconnects your app, revoke the token:

```typescript
await fetch("https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/revoke", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" },
  body: new URLSearchParams({
    token: tokens.refresh_token,
    token_type_hint: "refresh_token",
  }),
});
```

Users can also revoke your app's access from their Nocturne settings at any time.

## Scopes

Scopes control what your app can access. Request only what you need.

<OAuthScopeTable />

A `readwrite` scope always implies `read` — you don't need to request both.

<Callout type="info" title="Scope expansion">
  <code>health.read</code> and <code>health.readwrite</code> are convenience aliases.
  When you request one, the consent screen shows the individual scopes it expands to:
  glucose, treatments, devices, therapy, heart rate, step count, and food.
</Callout>
